Their only plays of more than a few yards were a few scrambles and one 14-yard run on third and 21.
For almost the entire second half of the game, Michigan's defense held Purdue to 1 yard of total offense.
More generally, Purdue came into the game averaging 6 yards per play and 25 first downs a game; Michigan held them to 3.8 and 9 first downs, only 1 in the second half.
The defense held Purdue to 9 yards on 5 combined drives, while the offense gained 279 yards on 33 plays for 21 points, which is 8.46 yards per play.
For the first time all year, Michigan's offense clicked.
